[R18] {'review_id': 'C5i08sgy5qjR-uEF4Bi2XA', 'user_id': 'arsk282rNqIbJIhmc-I6Iw', 'business_id': '2BRbu3cBbH2bCgzN3DVc8w', 'stars': 4.0, 'useful': 3, 'funny': 0, 'cool': 4, 'text': 'I have to be 100% honest...I yelp everywhere new I go and read some of the reviews before-hand and had a little bit of skepticism coming in.  It's always a great tool but with anything, it's all opinion based and this is absolutely one that I differ from the majority on.  

Table 31 was amazing.  We were taken exceptional care of by Justin who not only kept the glasses full but described every part/ingredient in the meal and when asked for an opinion, led us generously in the right way.

We started with drinks which were priced very fairly, we tried the "snail app" which is apparently a not very well kept secret and loved it...although I am not a fan of snails, my date was pleasantly surprised and loved the sauce and accompaniments with the dish.

From there we had House Made Cavatelli, the chef's specialty, and it was phenomenal.  We also sampled the lobster couscous and it was awesome. 

By the time the main entree came, we were stuffed but the steak was so delicious that I worked it in anyway.  The house cut fries as the side were some of the best I've had.

We were a little bummed that although we didn't have room for dessert, the one we were going to get anyway had run out for the evening...we'll be back for that.  The music was a little loud for dinner (coming from the bar) but the conversation was good enough to drain it out.  The beer selection was pretty lackluster but the wine & cocktail list more than made up for it.  To have Yuengling, in Philly is really all you need, honestly.

All in all, I would without a doubt return and it was so good, I had to review it and save some of the yelp-ers that will see the middle of the pack review and maybe looks elsewhere....give it a shot, you'll be surprised.', 'date': '2012-10-19 19:06:09', 'user': {'name': 'Jay', 'review_count': 24, 'yelping_since': '2011-08-17 16:19:13', 'elite': '', 'average_stars': 4.46, 'fans': 1}}
[R19] {'review_id': 'k-NAUJIqanLjq0t3ZtODGQ', 'user_id': 'ZwlyUe7_ilG-o3zGIzOppA', 'business_id': '2BRbu3cBbH2bCgzN3DVc8w', 'stars': 2.0, 'useful': 2, 'funny': 0, 'cool': 0, 'text': "I am sad that out of all the amazing restaurants in Philadelphia, we came here. The ambience is so alluring and trendy and we were starving after a long day at the Art Museum. Our waiter was very kind and really talked up the exclusivity and freshness of the menu. There was not much selection, so I ordered the house made cavatelli.

I do not mind paying an exorbitant amount for great dining, but please make sure my pasta doesn't taste like hard, uncooked macaroni noodles with ragu red sauce if you are charging that much.

Two stars for everything being pretty to look at.", 'date': '2012-10-12 16:33:48', 'user': {'name': 'Sunia', 'review_count': 163, 'yelping_since': '2012-04-30 22:53:05', 'elite': '', 'average_stars': 4.0, 'fans': 8}}
[R20] {'review_id': 'QF0xoOhe1bIUX7_YuxTE6g', 'user_id': 'sh8uZxH6zUTUsfbKlhI5Cw', 'business_id': '2BRbu3cBbH2bCgzN3DVc8w', 'stars': 1.0, 'useful': 0, 'funny': 0, 'cool': 0, 'text': 'Table 31 is a joke, and the punchline is that they took $150 from me.

DO NOT GO HERE!!!!! EVER!!!!!!!

My wife and I have been here two times prior, and it had been good if not great.  Tonight, the food was laughably bad.  If you didn't laugh, you would cry because each course was somehow bad.  While eating my food, I thought to myself "this food is on par with Chili's or TGIFriday's".

Table 31 reverse engineered restaurant week with the thought process of "ok each person pays $35, how do we profit from that?"

For our first courses, we ordered carpaccio and lasagna.  The lasagna was dry as it must have been sitting under a heat lamp for an hour or two.  It was on par with cafeteria lasagna.  As for the carpaccio, it was the coup de grace of the meal.  I would rate carpaccio as my top 10 favorite dishes.  In fact, my wife looked at all of the restaurant week participants and picked Table 31 as a surprise because she knows how much I love carpaccio!  I love the raw red meat, sliced so thinly that you can cut it with a fork.  

The waiter puts the carpaccio in front of me, and at first I thought that they forgot to put the carpaccio on my plate.  I realized that the carpaccio was white and blended into the plate.  It was plated with arugula, parmesan and a vinaigrette.  I am guessing it was pork, but honestly it tasted like turkey lunch meat.  The edge of the slices of meat were brown which meant to me that it was cooked somehow, and it tasted as if it was oven roasted.  The flavors did not blend well at all.  If someone gave me a plate of lunch meat and a salad, I may have preferred that over the carpaccio I had.

Next, we ordered the oven roasted chicken, the eggplant parmesan and a side of meatballs.  My wife's chicken was actually pretty good.  My eggplant was piping hot.  I could not touch it for about 5 minutes.  After waiting for a while, I finally took a bite and it burned my mouth a little bit, so much so that it took me another 5 minutes to actually taste eggplant.  The meatballs had way too much garlic.

For the dessert, we had the chocolate creme brûlée and panna cotta.  The chocolate creme brulee stunk.  We didn't even finish it.  Who doesn't finish chocolate!  My wife actually said "I mean, this doesn't taste good.  I feel like I am wasting calories by eating this."  With the panna cotta, it was ok not great.  The funniest thing about the whole meal was that on the panna cotta, they plated an assortment of fruits that were cut in half.  We got half a blueberry, not a full blueberry but a half a blueberry!  Who does that!  If the restaurant is too damn cheap to splurge on blueberries, then don't plate them!!!!!!  Oh and the blackberry was cut in half length wise, very weird.

This was probably the worst meal that I have eaten in Philadelphia in the 10 years that I have lived here.  And it cost me $150!  I am not that much of a foodie snob, but the meal was so bad that I was forced to create a yelp account to complain.

Please do not waste your time and money on Table 31.  There are so many great restaurants in Philly these days that are 1000x better than this place.

